1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 d5 5. Qa4 {This is only White's 7th choice,
according to statistics, but I find it is challenging. White deviates from
releasing the tension and intents to claim his superiority in the centre since
now the c6 pawn is pinned. It was employed by many top players,
including Magnus Carlsen.} e6 {This move is not really in the spirit of the
Grünfeld as now the Bc8 is locked, so Black's counter-attacking abilities are
limited. However, it still offers Black solid play similar to the Catalan.} (
5... Nbd7 {As after 5...Nfd7, Black provokes the early exchange on d5. However,
in this specific case Black faces problems with finding a good square for his
queen's knight.} 6. cxd5 Nb6 (6... cxd5 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bf4 Nb6 10.
Qb3 {leads to the same.}) 7. Qb3 {This is the most viable retreat. White keeps
an eye on the pawn on d5 and takes care of connecting the rooks as soon as it
possible.} ({Less promising is} 7. Qd1 cxd5 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. e3 O-O 10. Nge2 Bd7
11. b3 Bc6 12. O-O Nc8 $1 $11 {Black managed to solve the problem of his poor
knight in Leitao, R - Pirola, C Teresina 2017}) 7... cxd5 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O
10. Bf4 {The most flexible. White's rooks are ready for seizing the open
c-file now.} Ne4 (10... Bd7 11. Rc1 Bc6 12. Ne5 ({Weaker is} 12. Nbd2 Nbd7 {
, as in Wen, Y - Berkes, F Baku 2014}) 12... Rc8 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nd2 Nfd7 15.
Be3 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bd4 $14 {Black does not have compensation for his
structural drawbacks.}) (10... Bf5 11. Nc3 Ne4 {is another possible moves
order.} ({Dubious is} 11... Rc8 12. a4 Ne4 {, as in Danielian, E - Muzychuk, M
Astana KAZ 2019 White should have played} 13. a5 Nc4 14. Qxb7 Nxc3 15. bxc3
Nxa5 16. Qb5 Nc6 17. Ra6 $16 {Black's position is very passive, and the a7
pawn might fall at any moment.})) 11. Nc3 Bf5 (11... Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Bg4 ({
Black's position seems even more unpleasant after} 12... Bf5 13. Rac1 Qd7 14.
b3 Rfc8 15. Qa5 $16 {The Nb6 is stuck, and the a7 pawn is in permanent danger.
Movsesian,S - Bures,J Czechia 2015}) 13. b3 {It makes sense to restrict the
Nb6 right now.} ({Instead,} 13. Rac1 Qd7 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 {, as in Van
Wely,L - Dranov,A Germany 2015 might lead to unclear consequences after} Bxe2
$1 16. Rfe1 d4 $132) 13... Rc8 14. Qb4 {White had a slight- but long-lasting
pressure in Cernousek,L - Bednar,M Prague 2014}) 12. Rfc1 Rc8 (12... Qd7 13.
Ne5 Bxe5 {, as in Leko,P - Jones,G Hengshui CHN 2019 could be strongly met by}
14. dxe5 $1 $146 Rfc8 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Rd1 Qa4 17. Bg5 $36 {White's unopposed
dark-squared bishop is a monster.}) 13. Nb5 $1 a6 {This was Korpa,B - Pisu,R
Arad 2017 Now the simple} 14. Rxc8 Nxc8 15. Nc3 Nxc3 16. bxc3 {would have kept
Black under strong pressure - the pawns on b7 and d5 are weak.}) 6. Nf3 Nbd7 ({
Mostly,} 6... Bg7 {would not have independent value} 7. O-O (7. Qa3 {does not
offer much in view of} b5 $1 ({Weaker is} 7... Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 9. b3 $14 {
Andreikin,D - Kunte,A Reykjavik 2017}) 8. cxb5 cxb5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Bf4 b4 11.
Qb3 O-O $11) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 b6 9. Rd1 Bb7 (9... Ba6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Nc3 {
also transposes to the note below.}) 10. Nc3 Nbd7 {transposes to main line.} (
10... dxc4 $6 11. Ne5 {is a serious positional concession.})) 7. Qc2 {
Surprisingly, this natural move was never tested in practice. From c2, the
queen harmoniously covers the c4 pawn as well as supports the thematic e2-e4
break.} ({Harmless is} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. O-O Bg7 $11 {Djuric,S - Golod, V Ohrid
2001}) 7... Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Rd1 b6 ({The opposition of Black's queen and
White's rook is unpleasant, but} 9... Qe7 {is met by} 10. b3 {, when the Qe7
is not safe either, while} b5 {is somewhat committing. The play might continue:
} 11. Bb2 a5 12. a4 b4 13. Nbd2 Bb7 14. e4 $14) 10. Nc3 Bb7 ({Attacking the c4
pawn with} 10... Ba6 {turns out ineffective in view of} 11. b3 $1 Rc8 (11...
dxc4 12. bxc4 Bxc4 13. Nd2 Ba6 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Bxc6 Rc8 16. Qa4 $36) 12. e4 $1
dxc4 ({After} 12... dxe4 13. Ng5 Qe7 14. Ngxe4 c5 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. dxc5 Qxc5
17. Bf4 $14 {the Ba6 is obviously misplaced.}) 13. bxc4 Bxc4 14. e5 Nd5 15. Ne4
Ba6 16. Bg5 Qc7 ({Hardly better is} 16... f6 17. exf6 N7xf6 18. Re1 $36) 17.
Nd6 $36 {Black's position is crumbed.}) 11. Bf4 Qe7 (11... Rc8 12. e4 dxc4 13.
Qa4 $1 b5 14. Qxa7 Qb6 15. Qxb6 Nxb6 16. Bd6 Rfd8 17. e5 Nfd5 18. Nd2 $14) 12.
e4 {This advance is connected with a standard pawn sacrifice.} dxc4 {The most
challenging response.} (12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 {leads to an
extremely passive position, since Black cannot play c6-c5.}) 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bg5
Qe8 ({Too risky is} 14... f6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Ne4 Bxg5 17. Nfxg5 b5 18. Bh3
Nc7 19. b3 $36 {Black is a pawn up, but he has too many weaknesses.}) 15. Nd2
b5 16. Nde4 {The space advantage as well as the powerful Ne4 heading to d6
provide White with interesting compensation for the pawn.} *

