1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 d5 5. Qa4 Bg7 {By making this move Black
accepts the inferior pawn structure, but his lead in development partly
compensates for it.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Worth attention is} 6... O-O 7. e4 ({
Accepting the pawn sacrifice seems less attractive:} 7. dxc6 Nxc6 8. Nf3 Nd5 9.
O-O ({After} 9. e3 Nb6 10. Qd1 e5 $1 11. O-O Bg4 12. dxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nxe5
14. Nbd2 Rfd8 {Black obtained full compensation for the pawn in Vitiugov, N -
Vachier Lagrave,M Karlsruhe/Baden Baden 2018}) 9... Nb6 10. Qa3 Nxd4 11. Nxd4
Nc4 $1 ({But not} 11... Qxd4 $2 12. Nc3 Qf6 13. Rd1 $16 {Stupak,K - Manik,M
New Delhi 2019}) 12. Qb4 Qxd4 13. Nc3 Be6 $132 {, and Black is very active.})
7... cxd5 8. e5 Nfd7 9. Nc3 Nb6 10. Qd1 {The queen is coming back to its
initial square. However, it was not in vain - White has a big space advantage
now.} Nc6 11. Nge2 Bg4 {It is hard to find a good job for the bishop, but
giving it up is a certain concession} ({Another natural continuation is} 11...
f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 {Black liberates his bishop, but the pawn structure on the
kingside is exposed now.} ({Worse is} 12... exf6 $6 {, as in Vachier Lagrave, M
- Tari, A Douglas ENG 2018 which can be strongly met by} 13. Nf4 $146 Re8+ 14.
Be3 Be6 15. Nxe6 Rxe6 16. O-O $16) 13. O-O Bg7 14. b3 Bg4 15. Be3 Qd7 16. a4 $1
$14 {Black suffers from the poor Nb6 and the permanent structural drawbacks.})
12. h3 Bxe2 13. Nxe2 f6 14. f4 fxe5 15. dxe5 e6 16. b3 $14 {White was better
in Mamedyarov, S - Vachier Lagrave, M Saint Louis 2018}) 7. Nf3 Nb6 {Similary
to chapter, Black moves his knight to unlock the d-file and put
strong pressure on the d4 pawn.} (7... Bg4 {is traditionally met by} 8. Nbd2 {
, and then Black hardly has anything better than} Nb6 (8... Nd7 9. h3 Bxf3 10.
Nxf3 O-O 11. e4 Nc7 12. O-O {was better for White in Eljanov, P - Ipatov, A Baku
2015}) (8... O-O 9. O-O Nb6 ({Dubious is} 9... Qb6 $6 10. h3 Bxf3 $6 ({In case
of} 10... Be6 11. e4 Nb4 12. Ng5 $1 Bxd4 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qb3 $36 {White has
more than sufficient compensation, but it was still a better choice.}) 11. Nxf3
Nd7 12. e4 Nc7 13. Be3 $16 {White had both the powerful bishops and the strong
pawn centre in Grischuk, A - Radjabov, T Odessa 2008}) (9... Qc8 {also seems too
artificial.} 10. e4 Nb6 11. Qa3 Re8 {This was Vaganian,R - Bagirov,V Lvov 1978
Now my natural new idea is} 12. Ne5 $1 $146 Bh3 (12... Bxe5 13. dxe5 {offers
White a powerful initiative due to the pawn majority on the kingside.}) 13.
Bxh3 Qxh3 14. Ndf3 {, reaching a harmonious set up with a solid space advantage.
}) 10. Qa3 {again transposes to text.}) 9. Qa3 Na6 10. O-O O-O {, transposing
to the main line.}) (7... O-O 8. O-O Bg4 9. Nbd2) 8. Qa3 {This is the best.} ({
The drawback behind the other retreat can be illustrated in the following case:
} 8. Qc2 Bg4 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. O-O (10. e3 Na6 11. O-O c5 12. Qe4 Be6 13. Qxb7
Nb4 $36 {Black had a powerful initiative for the pawn in Bruzon Batista, L -
Zherebukh, Y Saint Louis USA 2018}) 10... Bxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Nb3 Qc4 {
Black can force the favourable exchange of queens.}) 8... Bg4 (8... O-O 9. O-O
Bg4 10. Nbd2 {transposes to text.}) ({Curiously, nobody tried} 8... Bxd4 $5
$146 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Be3 Qd6 11. Bc5 Qc7 12. Nd2 Na6 13. Be3 O-O 14. O-O {
The bishop pair and the vulnerability of Black's king prove White's
long-lasting compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Nbd2 O-O ({Another challenging
response is} 9... Bxd4 $146 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. h3 Bf5 (11... Be6 12. Nf3 Qd6 13.
Qc3 f6 14. Bf4 Qd5 15. O-O {feels dangerous for Black who lost harmony.}) 12.
Nb3 Qa4 ({After} 12... Qd6 13. Nc5 N8d7 14. Nxb7 Qxa3 15. bxa3 Rc8 16. Na5 c5
17. Nc6 $14 {The presence of the Nc6 in Black's camp is very annoying.}) 13.
Qxa4 Nxa4 14. Na5 Bc8 15. O-O) 10. O-O Na6 ({The somewhat more natural way of
development is} 10... N8d7 {, but it releases the pressure on d4 pawn.} 11. h3
Bxf3 12. Nxf3 e5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Qb3 $14) 11. e3 Qd6 ({If
Black insists on the c6-c5 break with} 11... Rc8 {White should play} 12. b4 $1
Qd7 (12... Nd5 13. Rb1 $14) 13. Rb1 Bf5 (13... Bh3 14. Bb2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 $14)
14. e4 Bg4 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Rfc1 $14 {, completing the development and
maintaining all the strategic merits.}) 12. b3 $146 {I find this natural move
very effective.} ({After} 12. Qa5 Bf5 13. b3 Qb4 14. Qxb4 Nxb4 {Black achieved
definite activity on the queenside in Pogonina, N - Gutierrez Olivares, D Caleta
ENG 2019}) 12... Rfd8 ({The standard} 12... c5 {does not work in view
of:} 13. Ne4 Qc7 14. Bb2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 cxd4 16. Rac1 Qd7 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. exd4
$36 {The poor location of the Na6 starts to tell.}) 13. h3 Bf5 14. Bb2 {
White's chances are preferable due to the superiority in the centre.} *

