1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 d5 5. Qa4 Nfd7 {A tricky move. In
comparison to the somewhat more natural 5...Nbd7, the queen's knight could go
to c6, whereas the Bg7 is unlocked now.} 6. cxd5 ({In case of} 6. Qc2 dxc4 7.
Qxc4 {Black wins a few tempi by attacking the queen and manages to neutralize
White's superiority in the centre:} Nb6 8. Qd3 Bg7 9. Nf3 Bf5 10. Qa3 Qd6 11.
O-O Qxa3 12. Nxa3 N8d7 {Black had a comfortable play in Svidler,P - Radjabov,T
Baku 2015}) 6... Nb6 7. Qd1 cxd5 8. e3 $5 {The idea to start with this
somewhat modest move is to limit the sudden activity of Black's minor pieces
on the queenside.} ({In case of} 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3 ({After} 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. O-O
O-O 11. e3 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e6 {White had only a symbolic advantage
due to the bishop pair in Ding Liren - Wang Hao Huai'an 2017}) 9... Bf5 $1 10.
Nge2 Nb4 11. O-O Bc2 12. Qe1 Bd3 $11 {White is unable to deviate from
repeating the moves.}) 8... Nc6 9. Ne2 Bg7 {The most common and natural
response.} ({However, Black can also try to develop fast play on the queenside
with} 9... Bf5 $5 10. O-O h5 11. Nbc3 $146 {This very natural move is a
novelty.} ({Instead,} 11. Nf4 {, as in Leko,P - Paravyan,D Moscow 2018 can be
strongly met by} e6 $1 12. Nc3 g5 13. Nd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 f5 {, and Black takes
over the initiative.}) 11... Rc8 12. b3 Nb4 ({After} 12... h4 13. Nf4 Nb4 14.
g4 $1 Bc2 (14... Rxc3 15. gxf5 {leads to the loss of material in view of the
threat 16.Bd2}) 15. Qd2 g5 16. Ba3 $1 $16 {The vulnerablity of his pieces puts
Black in a difficult situation.}) 13. h3 $1 {A decent prophylactic move.} (13.
a3 Nd3 14. Bd2 Nb2 $11 {leads to repetition.}) 13... e6 14. Qd2 Nd3 ({Too
risky is} 14... Nc2 {in view of} 15. e4 $1 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 Nxa1 17. Bd3 Bh6 18.
Qb2 Bxc1 19. Qxc1 Nxb3 20. axb3 $14 {Black has a rook and two pawns for two
pieces, but the king is in permanent danger.}) 15. a4 $1 {This move
illustrates the poor location of the Nb6 and vacates a3 for the bishop.} (15.
f3 Bb4 16. a3 Bxc3 17. Nxc3 Qc7 18. Ne2 Qc2 {yields Black sufficient
counter-play.}) 15... Bb4 16. Ba3 a5 $1 {At his turn, Black secures b4 for his
knight.} ({Worse is} 16... Bxa3 $6 17. Rxa3 Qe7 18. Raa1 Nb4 19. a5 Nd7 20. Ra4
$36) 17. f3 Qg5 {This is the only way to stop e3-e4.} 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. h4 Qh6
20. Rac1 {In the unbalanced position that arose White's chances seem
preferable due to the better coordination between the pieces.}) 10. Nbc3 O-O ({
It does not make sense to delay castling, since after} 10... Bg4 11. O-O Qd7
12. a4 $1 {the pressure on the d5 pawn forces Black to give up the bishop
anyway.}) 11. O-O Bg4 ({The pseudo-active} 11... Re8 12. b3 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 {
, as in Topalov, V - Giri, A London 2015 might lead to an unpleasant position
after} 14. Bb2 $146 Bg4 15. h3 Bf3 16. Nb5 Qd7 17. Nbd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $14 {
Black does not have any compensation for the isolated d5 pawn.}) ({Too passive
is} 11... e6 12. b3 a5 13. a4 Bd7 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Qd2 $14 {Roiz,M -Wagner,D
Dresden 2015}) 12. a4 $5 $146 {This innovation forces Black to either weaken
b5 or to give up his bishop immediately.} (12. h3 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Rc8 14. Bd2 e6
15. Rfc1 Nc4 16. Be1 Qd7 {was equal in Mis,M - Ln,Y Prague 2019}) 12... a5 ({
In the case of} 12... Bxe2 13. Qxe2 e6 14. b3 Rc8 15. Bd2 {it would take a long
time to re-locate the poor Nb6, so after} Nd7 16. Rfb1 Re8 17. a5 $14 {White
manages to seize space on the queenside.}) ({Of course, not} 12... e6 $4 13. f3
Bf5 14. g4 {, and the bishop is gone.}) 13. h3 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 e6 15. Nb5 Re8 (
15... Nc8 16. Bd2 Nd6 17. Rfc1 {is about the same.}) 16. Rd1 Nc8 17. Bd2 Nd6
18. Rdc1 {Black is under definite pressure along the c-file.} *

