1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 d5 5. Qa4 dxc4 6. Qxc4 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O
Bf5 {This position often arises after 5.Nf3 Bg7 6.0-0 0-0 7.Qb3, when 7...dxc4
is considered as an equal alternative to 7...Qb6.} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. h3 $5 {
A useful move which invites Black to show his cards. White secures e3 for the
bishop and also acquires the resource g3-g4 that might diminish Black's
control of e4.} ({Instead, the more popular continuations do not seem to offer
much:} 10. Re1 Ne4 11. Qb3 (11. Nh4 Be6 12. Qd3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 {Andriasian,Z -
Hovhannisyan,R Yerevan 2014} Rc8 14. e4 b5 $132) 11... Qa5 $1 12. Bf4 Nb6 13.
Ne5 (13. Be5 Bh6 14. e3 Be6 15. Qc2 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Nc4 17. e4 g5 {put White
under some pressure given the poor Be5 in Ribli, Z - Jankovic, A Austria
2012}) 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Be6 15. Qb4 Qxb4 16. cxb4 Rad8 {Black was fine in
Svidler, P - Can, E Baku 2015}) ({If White tries to reach the same with} 10. Qb3
Qb6 11. Re1 {, then Black can deviate by means of} Qxb3 12. axb3 Be6 13. b4 a6
14. e4 Nb6 15. Ng5 Bc4 16. Bh3 e6 {Black had a very solid position in Egelhof,
H - Wuttke,J GER email 2011}) 10... Ne4 ({Hardly a serious improvement either
is} 10... a5 11. Qb3 Nb6 12. a4 Be6 13. Qd1 Bc4 14. Re1 Nbd5 15. e4 $1 ({
Instead,} 15. Ne5 Ba6 16. Nd3 Nd7 17. e4 N5b6 {left the pawn on d4 very weak
in Narayanan,S - Chigaev,M Moscow RUS 2019}) 15... Nb4 16. Bg5 h6 17. Be3 {
White has a better position due to the powerful pawn centre.}) ({The other
natural move} 10... Rc8 {was seen in Huzman, A - Sasikiran, K Porto Carras 2018
Now my natural new idea is} 11. Qb3 $146 Qb6 ({Somewhat artifical looks} 11...
Nb6 12. Rd1 Ne4 13. Bf4 Be6 14. Qc2 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qd7 16. Ng5 Bc4 17. Ne4 Qf5
18. Rab1 $14) 12. Re1 Ne4 ({In comparison to 10.Qb3 Qb6 11.Re1,} 12... Qxb3 13.
axb3 {yields White an important tempo since the pawn on a7 hangs.} a6 14. e4
Be6 15. Ra3 h6 16. Be3 Rfd8 17. Rd1 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defence.})
13. g4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Be6 15. Qa3 c5 16. Bg5 Qd6 17. Rab1 b6 18. Red1 $14) 11.
Qb3 Qb6 ({The other way of covering the pawn is} 11... Nb6 {, but} 12. a4 $1 {
highlights the drawbacks of the Nb6. For instance,} a5 (12... Nd5 13. Nh4 Ndxc3
14. bxc3 Be6 15. Qc2 $14) 13. Rd1 Ra6 14. Ne1 Be6 15. Qc2 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Qc8 {
Avrukh, B - Gupta, A Istanbul 2012 Now White missed the strong} 17. Nd3 $1 Bxh3
18. Bxh3 Qxh3 19. Rb1 $36 {, regaining the pawn under favourable circumstances
since White's rook penetrates the opponent's camp.}) 12. Rd1 {White has
secured the pawn on d4, so now he can start challenging the Ne4.} Rfd8 ({After
} 12... Qxb3 13. axb3 Nb6 14. Ne1 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Be6 16. Rb1 $14 {White was
firmly in a control in Gelfand, B - Sutovsky, E Poikovsky RUS 2018}) 13. Bf4 h6
14. g4 $146 {This natural novelty is an improvement} ({over} 14. Ne1 Nxc3 15.
bxc3 {, as in Mitrabha,G - Gopal,G Kolkata 2019 Now the natural} e5 $1 16. Be3
Qc7 {would have offered Black excellent play.}) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Be4 16. Nd2
Bxg2 17. Kxg2 e5 (17... c5 18. Rab1 cxd4 19. cxd4 Qxb3 20. Nxb3 b6 21. Kf3 Rac8
22. Rbc1 $14) 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Ne4 Qc7 20. a4 b6 21. f3 {White has a slight,
but long-lasting positional advantage due to the more active pieces.} *

