1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 (6... Nb6 7. O-O
Nc6 {is another possible move order.}) 7. O-O Nb6 {By attacking the d4 pawn
immediately Black provokes e2-e3 and makes the early e7-e5 break possible.} (
7... O-O 8. e4 (8. Nc3 e5 9. Nxd5 ({After} 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 e4
12. Ne1 f5 {Black had nothing to worry about in Mamedyarov,S - Grischuk,A
Saint Louis USA 2018}) 9... e4 $1 10. Ne5 Qxd5 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. Bf4 Bg4 13. h3
Be6 14. Rc1 Qd5 15. Rxc7 Rac8 16. Rxc8 Rxc8 17. b3 Bxd4 {Kuzubov,Y - Erdos,V
Sovata ROU 2018}) 8... Nb6 9. d5 Na5 10. Qe1 Nac4 11. Nc3 e6 (11... Bg4 $6 12.
b3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ne5 14. Be2 $16 {Svidler,P - Artemiev,V St Petersburg RUS 2018
}) 12. Bg5 $5 $146 f6 13. Bc1 exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 ({After} 14... Bg4 15. h3 Bxf3
16. Bxf3 f5 17. Qd1 Nd6 18. Ne2 $1 $14 {the knight is heading towards e6, so
White's problems are undenieble.}) 15. Nd4 Nxc3 (15... Ndb6 16. Ne6 Bxe6 17.
Qxe6+ Kh8 18. Bxb7 {White regains the pawn in a favourable situation and
obtains a definite positional advantage.}) 16. Qxc3 Nb6 ({Hardly better is} 
16... Ne5 17. Rd1 Qe7 18. f4 Nf7 19. Re1 Qd6 20. Be3 $36) 17. Bf4 c6 18. Rad1 {
Black struggles to develop his bishop, so White has a powerful initiative.}) 8.
e3 (8. Nc3 Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Nb5 Qc4 11. a4 O-O 12. b3 Qg4 {proved to be
harmless in Nikolic, P - Kasparov, G Wijk aan Zee 2000}) 8... e5 (8... O-O 9. Nc3
{takes us to the main line.}) ({Dubious is} 8... Bg4 $6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 e5
11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Qe2 $14 {White has a stable advantage due to his
strong unopposed light-squared bishop in Krejci, J - Hrabusa, M Pardubice 2010})
9. Nc3 exd4 (9... Bg4 {was also tried by the great Garry, but it definitely
cannot be recommended for Black:} 10. d5 e4 (10... Ne7) 11. dxc6 Qxd1 12. Rxd1
Bxf3 (12... exf3 13. cxb7 Rb8 14. h3 fxg2 15. hxg4 Rxb7 16. Kxg2 $16 {Petrik,T
- Pacher,M Slovakia 2009}) 13. cxb7 Rb8 14. Bxf3 exf3 15. Ne4 Rxb7 16. Rb1 Na4
17. b3 O-O 18. Ba3 {White's advantage was undeniable due to the better pawn
structure in Kraemer, M - Plachetka, J Charleroi 2008}) (9... O-O 10. d5 {
is covered in a separate chapter.}) 10. exd4 O-O {We reached the important
tabiya. Visually, Black's position looks fine: the isolated d4 pawn is
vulnerable whereas Black has all chances to take control of d5.} ({Of course,
the greedy} 10... Nxd4 $2 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Bxd4 13. Nb5 $18 {leads to
disaster.}) 11. Bg5 $1 {White develops his bishops and interrupts the
coordination between the opponent's pieces.} f6 {This saves an important tempo,
but exposing the diagonal a2-g8 is a certain concession.} ({Any queen's
retreat has its drawbacks:} 11... Qd6 12. Bf4 Qb4 {This position took place in
Molenda - Zhigalko, Czech Republic 2019 Now White should have played} 13. Qc1
$146 Nxd4 (13... Bg4 {does not solve all the problems either:} 14. a3 Qc4 15.
Ne5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 c6 17. Re1 $14) 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Bxc7 $14) (11... Qd7 {
This is Black's first choice. The Qd7 locks the Bc8, but at least it cannot be
attacked by White's knights.} 12. Re1 h6 ({The challenging} 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4
Qxd4 {was tested in one correspondence game so far. In this case, the lack of
development in Black's camp immediately starts to tell:} 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Nb5
Bxb2 16. Rab1 Na4 ({Bad is} 16... Bg7 $2 17. Nxc7 Rb8 18. Be7 $18) ({The best
retreat is} 16... Bh8 {, but even then Black faces serious practical problems
after} 17. Be7 Bf5 18. Rbd1 Bg4 19. Rd3 $36) 17. Nxc7 Rb8 18. Nd5 Be6 19. Be7 {
Walczak,P - Krakovsky,P ICCF email 2010}) 13. Bf4 {The most active choice.} (
13. Be3 Nc4 {looks less attractive.}) 13... g5 ({The greedy} 13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4
Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Bxd4 16. Nb5 Bxb2 17. Rab1 $36 {leads to a dangerous situation
when Black suffers from lack of development.}) ({Too passive seems} 13... Ne7 {
, even though it was played by the 13th World Champion} 14. Qb3 c6 15. Ne4 $1 (
{Instead,} 15. Ne5 $6 Qd8 16. Rad1 Be6 {was fine for Black in Tkachiev, V -
Kasparov,G Cannes 2001}) 15... Nbd5 {the d5-square belongs only to one of
Black's knights!} 16. Bd6 Qd8 17. Ne5 Re8 18. Bc5 Nf5 19. Nc3 $14) 14. Be3 Nc4
15. Qc2 $5 $146 {This new move makes White's setup rather flexible.} (15. d5
Nxe3 16. Rxe3 Ne7 17. Ne5 Qd8 {led to an unclear position in Gunina, V -Terao, J
Tromso 2014}) 15... Nxe3 16. fxe3 Ne7 17. Rad1 c6 18. e4 {The vulnerability of
Black's king and the mobile pawn centre offer White promising play on the
kingside.}) 12. Qb3+ $1 {White takes the opportunity to connect the rooks with
tempo.} Kh8 (12... Rf7 {looks quite awkward and hardly can be an improvement:}
13. Bf4 Na5 14. Qb5 Nac4 15. d5 Bd7 16. Qb3 {Black was doomed to passive
defence in Jumabayev, R -Piorun, K Warsaw 2016}) 13. Bf4 Ne7 {This secures the
control of d5 for Black, but it delays the development of the Bc8.} ({I also
checked the following challenging reply:} 13... g5 $5 $146 14. Be3 g4 {This
looks very provocative, but after all Black wins the central pawn!} 15. Nh4
Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Qxd4 17. Nb5 {attacking the c7 pawn is a common approach in this
line.} Qc4 18. Qxc4 Nxc4 19. b3 Ne5 20. Nxc7 Rb8 21. Rfd1 Bd7 22. Rd6 $1 $14 {
White's next move 23.Ne6 would force the exchange of his light-squared bishop,
so Black is going to suffer from structural drawbacks.}) 14. Rfe1 Ned5 15. Bd2
c6 16. a4 $1 {This strong move illustrates Black's issues with the superfluous
Nb6 that is locked by the other knight.} a5 17. Ne4 Qc7 18. Rac1 $14 {White
was better in Cvitan, O - Moser, E Oberwart 2003} *

