1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O O-O {
This way of handling the position recently became quite popular on the high
level.} 8. e4 {White takes the upper hand in the centre, but Black's
dark-squared bishop is getting very strong.} ({It turns out that Black can
benefit from leaving his Nd5 for a while - in case of} 8. Nc3 e5 $1 9. Nxd5 ({
After} 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bd2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 e4 12. Ne1 f5 {Black had nothing to
worry about in Mamedyarov, S - Grischuk, A Saint Louis USA 2018}) 9... e4 $1 {
Black regains the piece under favourable circumstances:} 10. Ne5 ({Or} 10. Nd2
Qxd5 11. Nxe4 Qxd4 $11) 10... Qxd5 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. Bf4 Bg4 13. h3 Be6 14. Rc1
Qd5 15. Rxc7 Rac8 16. Rxc8 Rxc8 17. b3 Bxd4 {Black had no problems in Kuzubov,
Y - Erdos,V Sovata ROU 2018}) 8... Nb6 9. d5 Na5 {The Na5 is not as bad as it
looks. In such positions, Black mostly manages to re-locate it to c4.} (9... Ne5
{yields White an important tempo for completing the development:} 10. Nxe5
Bxe5 11. Nc3 e6 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Rc1 exd5 14. exd5 Bf5 15. b3 Rc8 16. Qd2 $14 {
Plischki, S - Simet,M Plzen 2015}) 10. Qe1 $5 {This somewhat unusual move
needs an explanation - White invites Black to solve the problem of the bad Na5.
It turns out that this is the only way of fighting against c7-c6.} ({For
instance,} 10. Nc3 c6 11. Bf4 Nac4 12. Qe2 e5 13. dxe6 ({Hardly stronger is} 
13. Bg5 f6 14. Bc1 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Be6 $11 {, as was played in a couple of games.
}) 13... Bxe6 14. Rac1 Bg4 15. Rfd1 Qe7 {was fine for Black in Roeber, B -
Pribyl, J Germany 1997}) 10... Nac4 11. Nc3 e6 {Black has to challenge the
centre as there is too little space for his pieces now.} ({Dubious is} 11...
Bg4 $6 12. b3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ne5 14. Be2 $16 {Svidler,P - Artemiev,V St
Petersburg RUS 2018}) ({The other natural move} 11... c6 $6 {is now weak in
view of} 12. b3 Nd6 13. e5 Nf5 14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Qe4 Be6 16. Rd1 Qc8 17. Bf4
Nd5 18. Ne2 {White was much better in Kurajica,B - Plenkovic,Z Zagreb 2014})
12. Bg5 $5 $146 {I was surprised to discover that this natural move was never
tested in practice. Provoking f7-f6 is an undenieble achievement for White.} ({
Instead, dozens of games saw} 12. b3 {, that might invite major
simplifications after} Qf6 $1 {For instance,} 13. bxc4 Qxc3 14. Qxc3 Bxc3 15.
Rb1 Nxc4 16. Bh6 Bg7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. dxe6 Bxe6 19. Rxb7 Nd6 20. Rxc7 Rfc8 {
when the draw is practically unavoidable.}) 12... f6 (12... Qd6 {definitely
cannot be recommended.} 13. b3 Ne5 14. Bf4 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 e5 16. Be3 $14) 13.
Bc1 {The bishop is coming back. Alas, there is no other possible square for
the retreat.} exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice is the most
challenging reply.} ({After} 14... Bg4 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 f5 17. Qd1 Nd6 18.
Ne2 $1 $14 {the knight is heading towards e6, so White's problems are
undeniable.}) 15. Nd4 {White's compensation is based on the pressure along the
h1-a8 diagonal and the weak e6-spot in the opponent's camp.} Nxc3 (15... Ndb6
16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. Qxe6+ Kh8 18. Bxb7 {White regains the pawn in a favourable
situation and obtains a definite positional advantage.}) 16. Qxc3 Nb6 ({
Hardly better is} 16... Ne5 17. Rd1 Qe7 18. f4 Nf7 19. Re1 Qd6 20. Be3 $36) 17.
Bf4 c6 18. Rad1 {Black struggles to develop his bishop, so White has a
powerful initiative. The following line illustrates White's dynamic resources
well:} Qe7 19. Rfe1 Qf7 20. Bd6 Rd8 21. Bc7 $1 ({Instead,} 21. Re7 Qc4 22. Qe3
Rxd6 23. b3 Qc5 24. Rxg7+ Kxg7 25. Qe7+ Kg8 {leads to draw by perpetual.})
21... Nd5 ({After} 21... Rd7 22. Bxb6 axb6 23. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 24. Qxc6 Rxd1 25.
Rxd1 Bb7 26. Qxb7 Qxb7 27. Bxb7 $16 {Despite the opposite-coloured bishops,
White has excellent winning chances.}) 22. Nxc6 $1 Nxc3 (22... bxc6 $2 23. Qxc6
$18 {leads to major loss of material.}) 23. Rxd8+ Bf8 24. Bd6 bxc6 25. Rxf8+
Qxf8 26. Bxf8 Kxf8 27. Bxc6 Rb8 28. bxc3 {White is a pawn up, so Black would
have to struggle hard for a draw until the end of the game.} *

