Germany 1996}) 16. Rab1 {This natural move is a novelty.} ({Instead,} 16. Bc3
Bxc3 17. bxc3 Ne5 18. Be2 Be6 19. Rd4 {yielded White a tiny advantage in
Tkachiev,V - Sutovsky,E Dresden 2007}) 16... Bf5 17. e4 Ne5 ({Also after} 17...
Bh3 18. b3 Nxd2 19. Rxd2 Rfe8 20. Rbd1 {Black is left without adequate
compensation for his structural drawbacks.}) 18. exf5 Nxf3+ 19. Kg2 Nxd2 20.
Rxd2 gxf5 21. Rbd1 {White has the better pawn structure and control over the
d-file, while Black is only nominally a pawn up.}) ({Definitely cannot be
