Nd2 $16 {Black was unready for fighting against the powerful
d6-passer in Shinkevich, V - Mingachev, M St Petersburg 2006}) (10... Ne7 11. e4
Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 c6 14. Rd1 cxd5 15. exd5 Nf5 16. d6 Rb8 17. Qd3 Qd7 (
17... Nd7 {temporarily sets up a blockade but does not solve Black's problems.
For instance,} 18. Ne4 Qb6 19. Bg5 Rfc8 20. Rac1 Nd4 21. Be7 f5 22. Ng5 e4 {
We have been following Mchedlishvili,M - Savchenko,B Subic Bay 2016 Now White
should have played} 23. Bxe4 $1 $146 fxe4 24. Qxe4 h6 25. Rxc8+ Rxc8 26. Ne6 {
, obtaining a decisive attack.}) ({The attempt to isolate the d6 pawn by means
of} 17... Nd4 {fails to} 18. Nb5 $1 Nd7 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Bd2 Re8 21. Rac1 {
White was much better in Van Wely,L - Leko,P Wijk aan Zee 2001}) 18. b3 Nd4 19.
Ba3 f5 20. Rac1 Rbc8 21. Ne2 e4 22. Qd2 $16 {Rasmussen,A - Andersen,M Hillerod
2010}) 11. b3 {Curiously, this natural move took place only in a few
high-level games so far. It seems vital to delay the activation of the
awkward Na5, even though it weakens the long diagonal.} (11. e4 {is by far
White's first choice, but after} c6 12. Bg5 ({Toothless is} 12. dxc6 Nxc6 13.
Bg5 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Bg4 $11) 12... f6 13. Be3 cxd5 14. Bxb6 Qxb6 15. Nxd5 Qd8
16. Rc1 Nc6 {Black is close to neutralize the activity of White's pieces and
reach equality. For instance,} 17. b4 ({Black had nothing to worry about
either after} 17. Qb3 Rf7 18. Rfd1 Be6 19. h4 Kh8 20. Kh2 Rd7 21. Bh3 f5 $11 {
Podgaets,M - Dvoirys,S Kharkov 1985}) 17... Bg4 18. Qb3 Kh8 19. b5 Na5 ({
But not} 19... Bxf3 $2 20. bxc6 bxc6 21. Rxc6 Bxg2 22. Kxg2 $16 {Kasparov,G -
Thorsteins,K (Saint John 1988}) 20. Qb4 Rf7 21. Rfd1 Rd7 $11 {Kucuksari,K -
Svedberg,H Tylosand 2017}) 11... e4 {The most challenging reply.} ({In case of
} 11... c6 12. dxc6 Nxc6 {Black manages to liberate his Na5, but gets under
strong positional pressure after} 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Ne4 Bf8 15. Qc1 $36) 12. Nd4
Nxd5 13. Nxe4 b6 {This move invites interesting tactical complications.} ({
Clearly worse is} 13... Qe7 $6 14. Bd2 Nc6 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Rc1 Ba6 17. Re1
$16 {Jumabayev,R - Darini,P Doha 2016}) 14. b4 $1 {Only this might pose Black
concrete problems in view of the vulnerablity of the queen's rook.} ({After} 
14. Ba3 c5 15. Nxc5 bxc5 16. Bxc5 Re8 17. b4 Ba6 18. bxa5 Bxf1 19. Qxf1 Rc8 {
White has enough play for the exchange, but not more.}) 14... Nxb4 15. Ba3 c5 (
