1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O Nb6 8.
Nc3 Nc6 9. e3 Re8 {This waiting move is known since the middle of the 60s.
Since Black fails to immediately solve his space problems with the immediate 9.
..e5, he tried to make this advance more effective. Quite soon it became the
main attempt to reach equality.} 10. h3 {This move was first introduced by the
talented GM Ratmir Kholmov back in 1965.} e5 {The most consistent.} ({Equally
popular is} 10... a5 11. d5 {, and now Black is at a crossroad:} ({Another
interesting way of handling the position is} 11. Qc2 $5 e5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13.
dxe5 Bxe5 14. e4 Qe7 (14... Be6 15. f4 Bd4+ 16. Kh2 $14) 15. Be3 Qb4 {This was
Yuffa, D - Kokarev, D Izhevsk 2013 Now the natural} 16. f4 $146 Bd4 (16... Nc4
17. Bf2 Bxc3 18. bxc3 $16) 17. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 18. Kh2 {would have offered White
excellent attacking prospects.}) 11... Bxc3 {This continuation leads to a
drastic change of the pawn structure.} (11... Ne5 {The most natural choice.
However, the exchange of knights makes it easier for White to advance his
central pawns.} 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. e4 e6 ({After} 13... c6 14. Re1 Bd7 15. Bh6
Rc8 16. Rc1 {Black was doomed to passive defence in Grischuk, A - Cheparinov, I
Loo 2013}) 14. Bh6 exd5 15. exd5 Nc4 {It looks like Black got some activity,
but White's next move increases the pressure} 16. Re1 $1 {It turns out that
White does not have to spend a tempo for covering his pawn.} Nd6 {This
position was reached in Dziuba, M - Grandelius, N Reykjavik 2013 Now White could
have maintained the merits of his setup by means of} ({The timid} 16... Nxb2 {
runs into} 17. Qc2 Nc4 18. Nb5 $1 Nd6 (18... Bxa1 19. Rxa1 Qf6 20. Rd1 $16) 19.
Rxe5 Rxe5 20. Nxc7 Rb8 21. Qc3 f6 22. Bf4 $36 {with powerful initiative.}) ({
Even worse is} 16... Bd7 $2 17. Rxe5 Nxe5 (17... Rxe5 18. Qd4 $18) 18. f4 $18 {
Sargissian,G - Navara,D Linares 2013}) 17. Qd2 $146 Bd7 18. Bg5 f6 19. Bf4 $14)
(11... Nb4 {This retreat looks somewhat unnatural since Black will be forced
to keep the knight on a6 for a while. However, this was tried by many good
players.} 12. e4 c6 {This is the most common way of challenging the centre.} ({
The standard alternative is} 12... e6 13. a3 Na6 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bc1 $1 {
White can afford moving the bishop back to its initial spot where it cannot be
attacked by the knight.} (15. Bf4 e5 16. Bc1 {, as in Favarel,A - Stany,G San
Sebastian 2017 does not seem to offer much in view of} Nc4 17. b3 Nd6 {, and
Black is very solid.}) 15... exd5 ({Perhaps, the lesser evil is} 15... e5 16.
b3 Bd7 17. Be3 {, but even then Black's position does not seem appealing: the
c7 pawn is weak, and the Na6 is misplaced.}) 16. exd5 Bd7 17. Re1 Nc4 18. Nd4
$36 {The weak e6-square causes Black serious problems.}) 13. a3 Na6 14. Be3 $1
{This move underlines the awkward location of the Nb6.} ({It makes less sense
to damage the opponent's pawn structure:} 14. dxc6 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 bxc6 16. Nd4 {
Now the pawn on c6 is weak, but Black obtains excellent piece play after} Bxd4
$1 17. Rxd4 Nc5 $132 {Osnos,V - Lukin,A Zaporozhye 1975}) 14... cxd5 ({The
other natural continuation -} 14... Nc4 {is strongly met by} 15. Qe2 $1 {
Giving up the strong bishop looks like a concession, but White
connects the rooks, so now his lead in development is getting serious.} Nxe3
16. Qxe3 Qd6 ({In case of} 16... cxd5 17. Nxd5 $1 e6 18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Rfd1 Qe7
20. e5 $16 {Black desperately lacks space.}) 17. e5 Qc5 {This was Kuljasevic, D
- Trbojevic, M Mali Losinj CRO 2018 Now my new natural idea is} 18. Nd4 Bd7 19.
Rac1 Qa7 20. Rfd1 $16 {Black's setup looks awful.}) 15. exd5 Bxc3 {With the
aim to simplify matters.} ({Too passive is} 15... Bd7 16. Bd4 e5 17. dxe6 Bxe6
18. Re1 {All White's pieces were much better in this position with symmetric
pawn structure in Yu, Y - Wan, Y Xinghua 2015}) 16. Bxb6 ({Worth attention is
also} 16. bxc3 $5 Nxd5 17. Bd4 Nac7 18. Qc1 Ne6 {This position occurred in
Kursova,M - Artemiev,V Yerevan 2014 , and now} 19. Be5 $1 $146 f6 20. Rd1 fxe5
21. Nxe5 Nec7 22. c4 $36 {would have allowed White to regain the piece whilst
maintaining all of the merits.}) 16... Qxb6 17. bxc3 Nc5 {Infante Machin,B -
Diaz Murgada, R Santa Clara 2015 Now White should have played} 18. Re1 Bf5 19.
Qd4 Qd6 20. Ra2 Rac8 21. Re3 $14 {Black's queenside play does not fully
compensate for the vulnerability of his king and the pressure along the e-file.
10.h3 a5 11.d5 Nb4 [Roiz,M]}) 12. dxc6 Bf6 {A correct retreat - it's important
to over-protect the pawn on e7.} ({Worse is} 12... Bg7 $6 13. Nd4 bxc6 14. Nxc6
Qd6 15. Qc2 e5 {, as in Serafimov, T - Le Roux, J Guingamp 2012 White should
have played} 16. Rd1 Qf6 17. Bd2 e4 18. Nd4 $16 {, obtaining a big positional
advantage.}) 13. Qc2 {White reasonably deviates from trading queens - Black
fails to find a good spot for the Qd8.} ({Less promising is} 13. Nd4 bxc6 14.
Nxc6 {Tennert,S - Laubsch,B Verden 2014} Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Be6 $11) 13... bxc6 14.
e4 $1 {A deep positional decision. True, the Bg2 is locked now, but it also
heavily restricts the activity of many Black's pieces!} (14. Rd1 {is well met
by} Bf5 15. Rxd8 Bxc2 16. Rxa8 Rxa8 {, and Black does not have any problems.})
({After} 14. Nd4 Bxd4 15. exd4 Bd7 16. Bh6 Nd5 17. Rfe1 a4 {White has full
compensation for the pawn, but it is hard to make any progress.}) 14... Be6 ({
In case of} 14... e5 15. Rd1 Bd7 16. Be3 Qe7 17. Rac1 Red8 18. h4 Bg7 19. Ne1 {
Black is left with no active counter-play, while White's knight is ready to
enter c5.}) ({Too passive is} 14... Bb7 15. Rd1 Qc8 16. Be3 a4 17. Rac1 e5 18.
a3 Qe6 19. Ng5 Bxg5 (19... Qb3 20. Qxb3 axb3 21. Rd3 $16) 20. Bxg5 f6 21. Be3
$14) 15. Rd1 Qc8 16. Bf4 $1 {White can afford to leave the h3-pawn uncovered.} (
{Instead,} 16. Kh2 a4 17. Nd4 a3 18. b3 c5 $1 19. Qxc5 Nd7 {provides Black
with enough counter-play due to the strong Bf6.}) 16... a4 {Black is trying to
get rid of his weak pawns.} (16... Bxh3 $6 17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. Qxc6 {Black's
position is sort of ruined, whereas White's king is still safe.}) 17. e5 {
A double-edged decision. Black acquires d5 for his pieces, but the Bf6 is now
passive.} Bg7 18. Qxc6 (18. Nd4 Nd5 19. Qxc6 Ra6 20. Qc1 Nxf4 21. Qxf4 Bxh3 {
leaves White with sufficient compensation, but not more.}) 18... Bd7 19. Qc1
Bxh3 20. Bxh3 Qxh3 21. Qxc7 Rab8 22. Qa7 e6 23. Rac1 $14 {White managed to
regain the pawn, while his pieces are still more active.}) ({We should also
consider other Black's moves that rarely can be seen in practice:} 10... h6 {
This is not the best among Black's waiting moves.} 11. Qe2 e5 {Well, this has
to be played now.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. e4 {Now the h6-pawn is sort
of hanging.} Be6 15. Rd1 Qf6 16. Bxh6 Qh8 17. Be3 Bxh3 18. Rac1 $14 {Black
regained the pawn, but faced serious problems with coordination between his
pieces in Haessel, D - Sarkar, J Berkeley 2008}) (10... Rb8 {This modest move
was made in the first game that saw 10.h3. It does not look in the spirit of
Black's energetic play in the Grünfeld.} 11. Qc2 $146 {This is my natural new
idea.} ({Less precise is} 11. Qe2 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 {, as in Kholmov,R-Jimenez
Zerquera,E Havana 1965 , since after} 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. e4 Be6 {the Qe2 is
more vulnerable and can be attacked by Black's bishop.}) 11... e5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5
13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. e4 Be6 15. b3 {This move heavily restricts the activity of
Black's minor pieces.} Qd4 16. Bb2 Qc5 17. Rae1 (17. Kh2 $5 Rbd8 18. f4 Bg7 19.
Rad1 {is also deserving of attention}) 17... Rbd8 (17... Bxg3 $2 {drops the
piece in view of} 18. b4 $18) 18. Kh2 Bg7 19. f4 c6 20. Re2 $14 {White has the
better position due to the space advantage and the poor Nb6.}) (10... Bd7 11.
Re1 $1 {White makes another useful move and invites Black to show his cards.}
Qc8 ({For some reason, after} 11... e5 {noone played} 12. Nxe5 $146 Nxe5 13.
dxe5 {, even though it looks very promising as the b7-pawn is hanging now.}
Rxe5 14. Bxb7 Rb8 15. Bg2 $14 {Black's compensation is insufficient.}) 12. Kh2
e5 {This position was reached in a couple of games (including top-level). At
this moment I like the following fresh idea:} 13. Nxe5 $146 ({Instead,} 13. d5
Na5 14. e4 c6 15. b3 cxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Nc6 {did not yield White any
advantage in Ramirez, A - Nakamura, H Saint Louis 2012}) 13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Rxe5
({Or} 14... Bxe5 15. Qc2 c5 16. e4 $14 {, starting the usual expansion in the
centre.}) 15. e4 Rh5 16. h4 c6 17. f4 $14 {The Rh5 is stuck, while White's
king is still absolutely safe.}) ({Artifical seems} 10... Be6 {, as it makes
e7-e5 impossible} 11. b3 a5 {This was Sirosh,I - Mosadeghpour,M Batumi 2018
White could have claimed superiority with} 12. Ba3 $146 a4 13. Ng5 Bf5 14. Nge4
$14 {The appearance of the knight on c5 would be very annoying.}) 11. d5 Na5
12. Qc2 {This move leaves White's setup quite flexible since the Bg2 remains
unlocked.} ({Another ambitious way of fighting for the initiative is} 12. e4 $5 c6
13. Re1 cxd5 14. exd5 {The pawn structure that arose usually means
confrontation!} Nac4 ({Dubious is} 14... f5 $6 15. Bg5 Qd6 16. Rc1 Bd7 17. b3 {
Black faced serious problems because of the poor Na5 in Greenfeld, A - Mestel, A
Beersheba 1988}) (14... h6 {was played in only one game, but it looks very
natural as g5 has to be covered. Here I like the following new idea:} 15. b3 $5
$146 (15. a4 $6 f5 {was better for Black in Jansen,C-Ragozin,E (2485)
Vlissingen 1999}) 15... e4 16. Nxe4 Bxa1 (16... Bf5 17. Nd4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 Rxe4
19. Bxe4 Nxd5 20. Bb2 {leaves White with a tiny advantage.}) 17. Bxh6 Rxe4 18.
Rxe4 Bf6 19. Bg5 Bxg5 (19... Bf5 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Rd4 $36) 20. Nxg5 Bf5 21.
Rh4 Qf6 22. Qd2 {offers White interesting compensation for the piece.}) 15. a4
$1 Nd6 (15... a5 16. Qb3 Bd7 17. Nd2 {The hanging Nb6 caused Black serious
problems in Donner, J - Poulsen, A Svendborg 1981}) 16. Ng5 $1 {White
energetically develops his initiative and does not let Black consolidate. In
particular, the strong Nd6 is going to be exchanged.} Bf5 17. a5 Nbc4 18. g4
Bd7 19. Nge4 {Black got under strong pressure in Vogel, J - Van Dop, A Eindhoven
1980}) 12... c6 {The most challenging - Black aims to liberate the Na5.} ({
The attempt to complicate the matters with} 12... e4 {does not work:}
13. Nxe4 Qe7 ({The timid} 13... Nxd5 $6 {runs into} 14. Rd1 Bf5 15. Nh4 $16 {
, and the pinned Nd5 causes Black serious problems.}) (13... Qxd5 14. Nd4 Qe5
15. Nc5 {put Black under strong pressure in Vrolijk, L - Kosakowski, J Wijk aan
Zee NED 2019}) 14. Nd4 Bxh3 15. Bxh3 Qxe4 16. Qxe4 Rxe4 17. Bg2 Ree8 18. Rd1
Rad8 19. e4 c6 20. Bg5 {The strong pawn centre that is supported by the
powerful bishops offers White the better chances.}) ({Dubious is} 12... Nac4 $6
13. Rd1 Nd6 14. e4 Bd7 (14... f5 {is traditionally met by} 15. Ng5 Qe7 16. a4
a5 17. b3 h6 18. Ne6 Bxe6 19. dxe6 Qxe6 20. Be3 {with a powerful initiative.})
15. a4 a5 16. b3 Qc8 17. Kh2 f5 18. Be3 $16 {Black is left with his structural
drawbacks and the poor Nb6 in Delorme, A - Olofsson Dolk, M Helsingor 2015}) 13.
b4 Nac4 14. dxc6 bxc6 {The strong Nc4 partly compensates for the weak c6-pawn.
White's main task is neutralizing Black's temporary activity.} 15. Rd1 Qe7 (
15... Qc7 $6 {,as in Rego,P - Paunovic,D Figueira da Foz 2014 should be met by}
16. Ne4 $1 f5 17. Nc5 e4 18. Nd4 $16 {, and White is firmly in a control.}) 16.
Nd2 Bf5 ({Premature is} 16... e4 {Iskusnyh,S -Timofeev,A Nizhny Tagil 2015} 17.
Nxc4 Nxc4 18. Rb1 Nb6 19. a4 {, and few Black's pawns are very weak.}) 17. Nce4
Rad8 ({It makes little sense to leave the queen's rook on its initial spot:} 
17... Red8 18. a3 a5 19. Nxc4 Rxd1+ 20. Qxd1 Nxc4 21. Qa4 {White was much
better in Ni, H - Gao, R China 2015}) 18. a3 $1 {The main idea of this modest
move would be clear soon.} h5 ({In case of} 18... Qd7 $146 {White can bravely
give up his pawn on h3 to force the exchange of the opponent's
light-squared bishop:} 19. Bf3 $1 Bxe4 20. Nxe4 Qxh3 21. a4 Rxd1+ 22. Bxd1 $36
{Black's position looks rather dicey.}) 19. Nxc4 Rxd1+ 20. Qxd1 Nxc4 21. Ra2 $1
{That's the point! It turns out that White can leave the Bc1 for a while and
still activate the rook.} Rd8 22. Qf1 Nd6 23. Nc5 Nb5 {A typical approach for
the Grünfeld - Black gives up his weak pawn to reach active
counter-play.} (23... e4 24. Rd2 Bc3 25. Rd1 $14) 24. Bxc6 Nc3 25. Rd2 Rxd2 26.
Bxd2 Qd6 $1 {This yields Black the bishop pair.} 27. Bxc3 Qxc6 28. e4 $146 {
White converts his material advantage into something else.} (28. Qg2 Qd6 29. e4
Qd1+ 30. Kh2 Bc8 {The activity of pieces gave Black sufficient compensation
for a pawn in Kramnik, V - Grischuk, A London 2013}) ({Worth attention is also} 
28. f3 $5 Bf8 29. Bxe5 Bxc5 30. bxc5 Qxc5 31. Bd4 Qxa3 32. g4 Bd3 33. Qe1 {
Despite the limited material balance, Black is in definite danger - the king is
very weak.}) 28... Bxe4 29. Nxe4 Qxe4 30. Bd2 Qc2 31. Be3 Qa4 32. Qd3 $14 {
Black has to struggle hard for a draw - potentially White can create a strong
passed pawn on the queenside.} *

