1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nb6 7. O-O Nc6 8. e3
O-O 9. Nc3 a5 {This move was first seen in 1946, but it gained popularity
mainly in the last 5-6 years. The main idea behind it is to make it difficult
for White to put his dark-squared bishop on b2.} 10. Qe2 {By making this move
White shows his intentions to extend in the centre.} e5 {This break seems most
reasonable now when there is no opposition to the Rd1 and Black's queen.} ({
The other possibilities are:} 10... Be6 11. Rd1 Bc4 ({In case of} 11... a4 12.
d5 $1 {works well again for White:} Nxd5 13. Nb5 $1 {This unexpected move
underlines the drawbacks of the opposition on the d-file.} ({Instead,} 13. Nxd5
Bxd5 14. Ne1 e6 15. e4 Nd4 16. Rxd4 Bxd4 17. exd5 exd5 $132 {is unclear.})
13... Qc8 14. Ng5 Rd8 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Rb1 $36) 12. Qc2 a4 {This was Popov,L
- Lukov, V Sofia 1982 Now White could have played} 13. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qc8
15. f4 $14 {, putting Black in a very passive position.}) ({The consistent} 
10... a4 11. Rd1 {offers White decent control over the centre} Bg4 12. h3 Be6 {
At this moment I propose the following fresh idea:} 13. d5 $5 $146 Nxd5 14. Nb5
$1 {This seems to be the best way of exploiting the lack of harmony in Black's
camp.} ({Instead,} 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Ne1 e6 16. e4 Nd4 17. Rxd4 Bxd4 18. exd5
exd5 {leads to an unbalanced position with mutual chances.}) 14... Qc8 15. Ng5
Rd8 16. Nxe6 fxe6 ({Of course, not} 16... Qxe6 $2 17. Rxd5 Rxd5 18. Nxc7 $18)
17. Rb1 Ne5 18. e4 Nb6 19. Bf4 {The bishop pair and the numerous weaknesses in
Black's camp offer White more than full compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Nxe5
Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 {Like in the main line with 9...Re8, this pawn structure
does not guarantee Black easy play - White can quickly extend on the kingside.}
13. Rd1 Qe7 14. e4 Be6 (14... a4 {hardly changes much:} 15. a3 Be6 16. Nd5 Bxd5
17. exd5 Qf6 18. Rb1 Rfe8 19. Be3 Re7 20. Qb5 $14 {Black was suffering from
lack of counter-play in Benko, P - Miles, A Lone Pine 1976}) ({The drawback of 9.
..a5 is perfectly illustrated in the following case:} 14... c6 15. Be3 Bc7 16.
f4 $14 {the poor Nb6 causes Black serious problems.}) 15. Nd5 Bxd5 {Giving up
the bishop pair is a concession,} ({but after} 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 Bf5 17. Bf4
Rfe8 18. Re1 f6 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Qd2 Qd6 21. Rac1 $14 {Black's position does
not look appealing because of the weak pawn on c7.}) 16. exd5 Rfe8 {This was
Mikhalchishin, A - Fogarasi, T Hungary 2008 Now my natural improvement over
White's play is} 17. Be3 Nc8 18. Re1 Nd6 19. Bf4 $14 {White's positional
advantage is undeniable.} *

