1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 O-O ({The immediate
} 6... c5 {is less viable, since after} 7. e4 {White has some additional
possibilities, such as} Nf6 (7... Nb6 8. d5 Bg4 (8... e6 9. O-O exd5 10. exd5
O-O ({After} 10... Qxd5 11. Re1+ Be6 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. Ng5 O-O 14. Nxe6 fxe6
15. Rxe6 $16 {the powerful Bg2 causes Black lots of problems.}) 11. Nc3 Bf5 12.
Bg5 Qd7 13. Re1 $16 {The powerful d-passer put Black in big danger in Bocharov,
D - Makarov, M Krasnoyarsk 2007}) 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 O-O 11. O-O N8d7 12. Nc3
c4 13. Qe2 Ne5 14. Be3 Nd3 15. a4 {White was much better in Sasikiran, K -
Sutovsky, E Mallorca 2004}) 8. d5 $1 {the e4-pawn is untouchable!} O-O 9. Nc3 e6
10. O-O exd5 11. exd5 Bf5 12. Re1 $16 {Plischki,S - Liska,J Teplice 2015}) 7.
O-O c5 8. e4 (8. dxc5 Na6 9. Ng5 e6 10. Ne4 Bd7 $1 {proved satisfactory for
Black.}) 8... Nf6 {This provokes White to advance his e-pawn.} (8... Nb6 9. d5
e6 10. Nc3 exd5 11. exd5 {is clealy better for White and was covered in the
above-mentioned note.}) 9. e5 Nd5 (9... Nfd7 {runs into} 10. e6 $1 fxe6 11. Ng5
{, and Black's positon is sort of ruined. For instance,} Qb6 ({Equally bad is} 
11... Nb6 12. Qe1 cxd4 13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. Qxe6+ Rf7 15. Bxb7 $16 {, as in the
correspondence game Sisбk,R - Saharinen,P ICCF 2016}) 12. Qe2 cxd4 13. Qxe6+
Qxe6 14. Nxe6 Nc6 15. Nxf8 Kxf8 16. Nd2 Nc5 17. Ne4 $16 {Black did not have
any compensation for the material deficit in Alavi, S - Vahidov, T Teheran 2016})
10. dxc5 Na6 (10... Nb4 11. Nc3 N8c6 12. a3 Nd3 {We have been following the
classical game Botvinnik, M-Bronstein, D Moscow 1951 At this moment I suggest
the following new idea:} 13. Qe2 $5 $146 Bg4 14. Rd1 Nxc1 15. Raxc1 Qc7 16. Qe4
Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qxe5 18. Qxe5 Bxe5 19. Rd7 $16 {The control over the 7th rank
and the pawn majority on the queenside offer White a huge positional advantage.
}) (10... Nc6 {This continuation was played in a few games. Now I mostly like
the following new idea:} 11. Bg5 $5 $146 h6 ({After} 11... Bg4 12. h3 Be6 13.
Nd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 h6 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. Nc3 $16 {Black fails to regain the pawn
and suffers from the poor Bg7.}) 12. Bd2 {By provoking h7-h6 White wins an
important tempo, so his queen can leave d1 soon.} Be6 13. Qc1 Kh7 14. Rd1 Qb8
15. Nc3 $36) 11. Qd4 $1 {Curiously, this strong move was only tested in a few
games. The queen not only covers the pawn on c5 but at the same time, it can
also be transferred to h4.} ({The most common alternative -} 11. a3 {was
suggested by Boris Avrukh in his great series on 1.d4 (volume two) and was
subsequently seen in many games afterwards. However, it seems less promising
because of} Nxc5 12. b4 Ne6 13. Qb3 Nb6 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. Nc3 Qc4 $1 16. Qxc4
Nxc4 17. Nd5 Re8 {Black was close to equality in Wojtyra, S - Pietrzak, J email
2013}) 11... Ndb4 {This is the only viable response.} (11... Bf5 12. Nc3 Nxc3
13. Qxc3 Qd3 14. Qxd3 Bxd3 15. Rd1 Be2 16. Rd7 Nxc5 17. Rxe7 {leaves Black
with no compensation for the pawn.}) 12. Qh4 Nc2 {The Ra1 is trapped, but...}
13. Bg5 $1 {All of White's pieces are getting very active now.} Qd7 ({After} 
13... Re8 14. Nc3 Nxa1 15. Rxa1 Nxc5 16. Rd1 Bd7 17. Nd5 Bf8 18. Bh6 Ne6 19.
Bxf8 Nxf8 20. Qh6 $40 {Black hardly can withstand such a massive attack.}) 14.
Nc3 Nxa1 15. Rxa1 f6 16. Qc4+ $1 {This intermediate check makes it possible
for White to deviate from exchanging queens.} ({Instead,} 16. Be3 $6 Qg4 {
led to an unbalanced endgame with mutual chances in Wojtaszek, R - Tomczak, J
Warsaw POL 2018}) 16... Kh8 ({The same type of position arises after} 16... Qe6
17. Nd5 $1 Qf7 18. exf6 exf6 19. Bf4 $16) 17. Be3 Qg4 18. Nd4 fxe5 19. h3 Qd7
20. Ndb5 $16 {Black's material advantage only has a symbolic value - White
dominates over the board.} *

